uid":"9CA535DF4A274566841E4C6D0AC7B220","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"D3A39091B13C4B2793F36147C54BE22A","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">An optional step <\/span><span>if your end-resulting plasmid does not have internal BsaI\/Esp31 sites within the insert or backbone vector (other than the ones used for the assembly of insert and vector), you can add ATP-dependent DNase (Lucigen E3101K - Plasmid-Safe\u2122 ATP-Dependent DNase) which digests linear DNA but not circular DNA. Add <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">  of Plasmidsafe DNase and <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> of 25 mM ATP to the Golden Gate reaction and incubate at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> for <\/div><br\/><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"F3F81CA0A4E211EBBB7EF938748EE67E","order_id":2,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":0.25,"unit":"\u00b5l","title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"074FBDD0A4E311EBBB7EF938748EE67E","order_id":3,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":0.5,"unit":"\u00b5l","title":""}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"1D4625C0A4E311EBBB7EF938748EE67E","order_id":4,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":37,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054728,"guid":"25B1E8C0A4E311EBBB7EF938748EE67E","order_id":5,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":900,"title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":900},{"id":1166860,"guid":"EE199430A4E211EBBB7EF938748EE67E","previous_id":1166859,"previous_guid":"6FF1E4E0A4E211EBBB7EF938748EE67E","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"5EA19B4F9EF3417391451AF35FC435D5","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"3A6C46A137754DCD803CD864120FC4C8","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Transform the Golden Gate reaction into <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">E. coli<\/span><span> cells (e.g. DH5\u0251, Mach1, TOP10, NEB10\u03b2), following an appropriate protocol.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>This protocol is for the assembly of DNA parts using Golden Gate assembly (Engler et al. 2008) with modifications from on publication by Garcia-Ruiz et al. (2018) and online resource by NEB (<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/international.neb.com\/protocols\/2018\/10\/02\/golden-gate-assembly-protocol-for-using-neb-golden-gate-assembly-mix-e1601\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">https:\/\/international.neb.com\/protocols\/2018\/10\/02\/golden-gate-assembly-protocol-for-using-neb-golden-gate-assembly-mix-e1601<\/span><\/a><span>).<\/span><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">Parts can either be assembled by Golden Gate assembly using Esp31 or Bsa1v2-HF depending on the restriction sites flanking the parts. Using this protocol, multiple insert parts can be assembled into the parts acceptor vector. The Golden Gate assembly reaction is incubated in a thermocycling program set at a digestion temperature of at 37\u2103 and ligation temperature of 16\u2103 for 20-30 cycles. The reaction is subsequently transformed into E. coli cells (DH5\u0251, Mach1, TOP10, NEB10\u03b2).<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">1. Engler\u00a0C, Kandzia\u00a0R, Marillonnet\u00a0S (2008)A One Pot, One Step, Precision Cloning Method with High Throughput Capability. PLOS ONE 3(11): e3647. doi: 10.1371\/journal.pone.0003647<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">2. Garcia-Ruiz E, Auxillos J, Li T, Dai J, Cai Y. YeastFab: High-Throughput Genetic Parts Construction, Measurement, and Pathway Engineering in Yeast. Methods Enzymol. 2018;608:277-306. doi: 10.1016\/bs.mie.2018.05.003.<\/div><br\/><\/div>","changed_on":1628440624}